A SECURITY GUARD SMELLED AMMONIA AND REPORTED IT TO HIS SUPERVISOR, AND HIS SUPERVISOR HAD HIM TAKEN TO A HOSPITAL TO BE "CHECKED OUT".  WHEN THE CAR HE WAS NEXT TO WHEN HE SMELLED AMMONIA WAS INSPECTED, IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE A DETERIORATED GASKET IN THE SRV O-RING CAP.  THIS GASKET WAS REPLACED, STOPPING THE VERY MINOR VAPOR LEAK WITHIN THE MANWAY PRESSURE NOZZLE.  THE SECURITY GUARD WAS "CHECKED OUT" AT THE MEDICAL FACILITY AND TOLD HE HAD NO SYMPTOMS OF AMMONIA EXPOSURE.  THE GUARD WAS RELEASED THAT NIGHT, AND IN FACT DID RETURN TO COMPLETE HIS SHIFT AND HAS SINCE EXPERIENCED NO ILL EFFECTS FROM THE SMELL HE RECEIVED.

CHAMBLEE, GEORGIA FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORTED THE STRONG ODOR OF DIESEL FUEL TO CARRIER PERSONNEL.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED SOU 95034 HAD ROLLED FREE FROM WHERE THE CAR HAD BEEN SPOTTED FOR UNLOADING RESULTING IN THE BREAKAGE OF THE UNLOADING HOSE CONNECTED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  ALL CONTENTS OF THE CAR HAD ESCAPED BY THE TIME THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED. CARRIER PERSONNEL, STATE AND FEDERAL ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICIALS AND PRIVATE CONTRACTOR EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY BEGAN EFFORTS TO CONTAIN AND CONTROL THE SPILL.  REMEDIATION EFFORTS WERE SUCCESSFULLY COMPLETED ON 12-10-91. THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT REMAINS UNDER INVESTIGATION, HOWEVER, PRELIMINARY INDICATIONS ARE THE HANDBRAKE WAS RELEASED BY TRESPASSERS ALLOWING THE TANK CAR TO ROLL OVER A DERAILER DEVICE.
DURING UNLOADING DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED ONE PAIL WITH AN APPARENT FORKLIFT PUNCTURE NEAR THE BOTTOM.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND DAMAGED PAIL WAS RECOUPED.
DOCKWORKER ADVISED SUPERVISOR THAT ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING AT THE SEAM.  ALL SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT AND THE DRUM WAS FORWARDED.

DOCKWORKER NOTICED AN ODOR UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOOR FOR UNLOADING. UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  THE FREIGHT BILL WAS SECURED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND CLEANUP INSTRUCTIONS WERE OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHEN DOCKWORKER OPENED TRAILER DOOR FOR UNLOADING, HE DISCOVERED LEAKAGE FROM AN APPARENT FORKLIFT PUNCTURE IN ONE DRUM AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE FREIGHT BILL SECURED.  THE MATERAIL WAS IDENTIFIED AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK CONSULTED.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS LAID ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE AND ALL RELEASED MATERIAL HAD DRIED.

MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING THROUGH A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF ONE DRUM AND THE AREA WAS ISOLATED.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE CONTACTED AND MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AS INSTRUCTED.  DAMAGED DRUM WAS RECOVERED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS INSTRUCTED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM, OUR DRIVER LEFT LEWISBURG, TENNESSEE, EN ROUTE ALONG HIGHWAY 64 TO SHELBYVILLE, TENNESSEE, WHICH IS APPROXIMAELY A DISTANCE OF 30 MILES.  AT THE DRIVER'S LAST STOP IN LEWISBURG, HE NOTICED NOTHING UNUSUAL REGARDING A 300 GALLON TOTE TANK OF 10% SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE.  THE TANK IN QUESTION IS #48051.  UPON ARRIVAL AT CUSTOMER LOCATION IN SHELBYVILLE, HE FOUND THE TANK TO BE EMPTY OF MATERIAL.  AFTER INSPECTION OF THE UNIT HE FOUND A TEAR OF SEPARATION OF THE TANK FROM WHICH THE MATERIAL OBVIOUSLY ESCAPED.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED HIS BRANCH.  AFTER THE BRANCH GOT THE DETAILS FROM THE DRIVER, THEY CALLED THE CORPORATED OFFICE.  THE CORPORATE OFFICE ADVISED THAT THIS WAS A REPORTABLE QUANTITY AND HAD TO BE REPORTED.  AT THAT POINT, THE FOLLOWING PROPLE WERE NOTIFIED: RICK STEVENS OF CHEMTREC (CASE #11579), BRIAN BESHOAR OF NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #98079), AND GARY BEASELEY OF TENNESSEE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY (TEMS) (INCIDENT #1266).

column168: JB HUNT VEHICLE ALLEGEDLY LEFT ROADWAY AND STRUCK A PARKED TRANSPORT BUS ON SHOULDER OF ROADWAY. RT SIDE TRAILER OF JB HUNT VEHICLE HEAVILY DAMAGED AND CARGO LOADED NEXT TO WALL, INSIDE TRAILER, ALSO DAMAGED. MAJORITY OF SPILL OF PAINT REMAINED IN TRAILER WITH SOME SPILLED ON PAVED SURFACE OF ROADWAY. REMAINING PAINT IN TRAILER WAS REMOVED, FILTERED AND RE-USE BY WREDKER SERVICE.
DRIVER OVER FILLED TANK AND CAUSE ONE GALLON SPILL. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP. DRIVER WAS REMINDED HOW TO GAUGE & FILL TANK.

THE DRIVER FINISHED USING TRUCK CARGO PUMP, UNLOADING INTO THE REFINERY ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. HE UNHOOKED HIS DISCHARGE HOSE BEFORE CLOSING THE TANK OUTLET VALVE. THE TANK OUTLET VALVE HAD A BACKUP CHECK VALVE, BUT (AS IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED BY A MECHANIC) THERE WAS A ROCK INSIDE THE VALVE BLOCKING THE SEAT OPEN WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO FLOW BACK THROUGH THE LINE AND SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. THE REFINERY FIRE DEPT FOAMED THE SPILL AND THEIR CLEAN UP CREW VACUUMED UP THE LIQUID AND DISPOSED OF THE CONTAMINATED GRAVEL.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT DELIVERY STOP, THE DRIVER NOTICED A DRUM ON A PALLET HAD LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK.  UPON INVESTIGATION, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A NAIL ON THE PALLET HAD POPPED UP DURING TRANSPORTATION AND HAD POKED A HOLE INTO THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF NINE PLASTIC DEL DRUMS BANDED TOGETHER ON A PALLET.  THE DRIVER CUT THE BAND, TIGHTENED THE BUNGS, TURNED THE LEAKING DRUM HOLE-UP AND THEN PLACED IT INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO THE PLANT. RECOMMENDATIONS FOR IMPROVED HANDLING: 1.REVIEW WITH DRUM HANDLERS, THE IMPORTANCE AND NECESSITY OF CHECKING THE CONDITION OF PALLETS BEFORE PLACING DRUMS THEREON FOR STORAGE. 2. REVIEW WITH DRIVERS, THE PROPER PROCEDURES FOR INSPECTING THE CONDITION OF THEIR LOADS BEFORE AND DURING DELIVERY.

THE DRIVER WENT TO HOSPITAL BECAUSE OF REDNESS AND IRRITATION TO SKIN.

NO REMARKS.

OS&D WAS CONTACTED TO INSPECT DAMAGED, THE BAGS WERE INDIVIDUALLY REMOVED FROM SKID AND PLACED ON FRESH SKID.  THREE OF THE BAGS ST THE BOTTOM OF SKID WERE FOUND PUNCTURED, THEY WERE TAPED AND PLACED INTO POLY BAGS THEN PUT INTO 55 GAL DRUM WHICH ALL THE SPILLED FLAKE WAS ALSO RECOVRED INTO.  THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS THEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE AND AT THE END OF THE DELIVERY THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE OVERFLOWED.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN A DIKE AROUND THE STORAGE TANK.

APPROXIMATELY 60 GALLONS WAS SPILLED BEFORE THE PRODUCT FLOW COULD BE STOPPED.  THIS WAS CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND CLEANED UP FOR SUBSEQUENT DISPOSAL BY SHIPPER PERSONNEL.

column168: LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (FS), INC. INCURRED A HAZARDOUS WASTE SPILLAGE ON DECEMBER 26, 1991, BETWEEN 5:00 AND 6:00 AM.  THE SPILLAGE OCCURRED AT 510 NORTH HAZEL STREET IN SULPHUR, LOUISIANA (70063), WHERE ITS TRANSPORTATION TERMINAL IS LOCATED.  NO EPA IDENTIFICATION NUMBER IS ASSIGNED TO THIS LOCATION FOR THE GENERATION OF HAZARDOUS WASTE. A DRIVER WAS PUTTING AN OPEN-TOP ROLL-OFF CONTAINER ON A ROLL-OFF FRAME TRAILER WHEN APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS SPILLED. THE USDOT DESCRIPTION OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS "RQ HAZARDOUS WASTE, N.O.S., ORM-E, NA 9189 (CRESOTE)".  A CLEANUP OF THE SPILLAGE WAS EXECUTED, AND AS A RESULT, FIVE 55-GALLON DRUMS OF MATERIAL WAS GENERATED. WE CONTACTED THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  THE INCIDENT NUMBER ASSIGNED BY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 91-3765 AND 101141, RESPECTIVELY.  A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT REPORT (DOT FORM 5800.1) WILL BE COMPLETED AND FORWARDED TO THE UNITED STATES DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION IN WASHINGTON, D.C. WITHIN THE NEXT THIRTY DAYS. ON DECEMBER 30, 1991, THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY ASSIGNED A TEMPORARY EPA IDENTIFICATION NUMBER TO THE SITE WHERE THE SPILLAGE OCCURRED.  IT IS LAP 230067626.  THIS NUMBER IS REQUIRED SINCE LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (FS), INC. IS THE GENERATOR OF THE MATERIAL COLLECTED DURING THE CLEANUP EFFORT. NOTE: DRIVER WILL RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING IN RESPECT TO THE LOADING AND UNLOADING OF ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS.

column168: SHIPPER LEFT TWO PACKAGES AT SANTA MARIA AIRPORT, WESTAIR COUNTER FOR COMPANY SHIPMENT "COMAT" TO FRESNO.  THE PACKAGES CONTAINED AIRCRAFT PAINT AND A CHEMICAL THAT IS USED IN APPLICATION OF THE PAINT.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT LABELS AFFIXED TO EITHER BOX.  THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED AN INVOICE FROM AEROFLAIR WITH ORDERS TO SHIP TO WESTAIR. THE AGENT WHO RECEIVED THE SHIPMENT AFFIXED A "COMAT" STICKER TO BOTH PACKAGES AND PLACED THEM ON A FLIGHT TO SAN FRANCISCO AT WHICH POINT A CONNECTION TO FRESNO WOULD BE MADE.  AT SAN FRANCISCO, THE SHIPMENT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER AIRCRAFT AND FLOWN TO FRESNO.  DURING THIS FLIGHT, ONE OF THE CONTAINERS DEVELOPED A LEAK.  UPON ARRIVAL IN FRESNO, THE AGENT WHO OPENED THE CARGO DOOR OF THE AIRCRAFT NOTICED FUMES ESCAPING FROM THE PACKAGE.  HE REMOVED THE PACKAGE AND NOTIFIED THE AIRCRAFT CREW.  THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ALSO CALLED.  THERE WAS NO FIRE NOR WAS THERE ANY DAMAGE TO THE AIRCRAFT OR OTHER BAGGAGE/CARGO. WESTAIR MAINTAINS A POLICY OF NOT CARRYING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WITH THE EXCEPTIONS OF LIMITED QUANTITIES OF DRY ICE, CERTAIN MEDICAL SHIPMENTS AND WHEEL CHAIR BATTERIES.  WESTAIR'S PRIMARY SERVICE OF BUSINESS IS PASSENGERS.  GROUND AND FLIGHT PERSONNEL ARE TRAINED IN RECOGNITION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND ARE SUPPOSED TO ENSURE THAT SUCH SHIPMENTS ARE NOT LOADED ON AIRCRAFT.  THE PRIMARY MEANS OF RECOGNITION IS THE D.O.T. LABEL. THE AGENT IN SANTA MARIA WAS TRAINED ON HAZMAT AND HIS LAST TEST WAS ON JUNE 12, 1991. SINCE NO LABELS WERE AFFIXED TO THE TWO BOXES, THE AGENT WAS NOT ALERTED TO THE NATURE OF THE CONTENTS.  SINCE THE SHIPMENT WAS AT THE REQUEST OF THE COMPANY PURCHASING DEPARTMENT, THIS FURTHER CAUSED THE AGENT TO BELIEVE THAT IT WAS APPROPRIATE TO LOAD IT ON THE AIRCRAFT.  DURING THE TRANSFER IN SAN FRANCISCO, THERE WAS NO OBSERVATION OF LEAKAGE OR ANY PROBLEM AND, ONCE AGAIN, THE TWO BOXES APPEARED TO BE TYPICAL "COMAT" SHIPMENTS.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THEIR POSITION IN THE CARGO COMPARTMENT DURING THE FLIGHT FROM SAN FRANCISCO TO FRESNO CAUSED THE CONTENTS OF ONE BOX TO SHIFT AND THE LEAKAGE THEN OCCURRED. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED BY THE CAPTAIN OF THE AIRCRAFT AT 20:30 ON DECEMBER 26, 1991.  A TELEPHONE REPORT WAS MADE TO THE FAA BURLINGAME FSDO THE NEXT MORNING.  PERSONNEL WERE NOT AWARE THE BURLINGAME FSDO COULD RECEIVE SUCH A REPORT AT NIGHT.  THEY ARE NOT AWARE AND ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS WILL RESULT IN THE TELEPHONE REPORT BEING MADE IMMEDIATELY. A SHIPPER IN SANTA MARIA IS AN AIRCRAFT PAINT SHOP THAT HAS HAD A LONG-STANDING BUSINESS RELATIONSHIP WITH THE COMPANY.  THIS PAINT SHOP HAD, IN THE PAST, SHIPPED AIRCRAFT PARTS AND OTHER NON HAZARDOUS ITEMS ON COMPANY FLIGHTS.  THIS PARTICULAR SHIPMENT WAS MADE IN THE ORIGINAL BOX THAT THE PAINT WAS DELIVERED IN AND THE SHIPPER BELIEVED THAT THIS WAS AN APPROPRIATE CONTAINER FOR THE INTENDED PURPOSE.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOT AWARE OF THE COMPANY HAZMAT PROCEDURES ON THE DATE OF THE SHIPMENT. IN RESPONSE TO THIS INCIDENT, THE COMPANY HAS TAKEN

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HOURS, THURSDAY, DECEMBER 19, 1991, CONRAIL TRAIN WSKE-10 DERAILED FOUR (4) TANK CARS AT APPROXIMATE MILEPOST 26.1 OF THE CONRAIL ALGERS INDUSTRIAL TRACK IN KENTON, OH.  TRAIN CREW HAD JUST COMPLETED SWITCHING THE OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL COMPANY PLANT AND WAS PROCEEDING NORTH OUT OF THE PLANT ON A LEAD TRACK WHEN THE DERAILMENT OCCURRED.  DERAILMENT WAS CAUSED BY WIDE GAUGE TRACKS DUE TO DETERIORATED TIES.  ONE OF THE FOUR DERAILED CARS, GATX-34196 (LOADED TANK CAR OF HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID NOS) DERAILED ONTO ITS SOUTH SIDE AND APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLON OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE MANWAY. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL WERE ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK AND PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY PERSONNEL FROM OH MATERIAL FROM FINDLAY, OH. ALL CARS WERE RERAILED BY CONRAIL MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL. OTHER CARS INVOLVED INCLUDED UTLX-74095 (EMPTY TANK CAR - PETROLEUM LUBRICATING OIL), GATX-300224 (EMPTY TANK CAR -PHENOL) AND UTLX-650361 (EMPTY TANK CAR - PHENOL).

AT APPROXIMATELY 0510 HOURS, SATURDAY, DECEMBER 28, 1991, TANK CAR TILX-1100 (RESIDUE HYDROCHLORIC ACID) DERAILED AND SUSTAINED PUNCTURE DAMAGE TO THE TANK CAR SHELL DURING A RAIL ACCIDENT AT THE CONRAIL RAIL YARD IN ELKHART, INDIANA.  AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, TRAIN EJEL-8 WAS ARRIVING ON RECEIVING TRACK #15 WHEN THIRTY-FIVE CARS LOCATED ON RECEIVING TRACK #14 ROLLED INTO THE SIDE OF TRAIL EJEL-8.  ELEVEN TOTAL CARS DERAILED WITH THE TILX-110000 BEING THE ONLY HAZARDOUS CAR INVOLVED. INCIDENT CAUSE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER SECURING OF RAIL CARS ON RECEIVING TRACK #14.  TILX-110000 SUSTAINED A 2 FOOT BY 3 FOOT PUNCTURE IN ONE END OF THE TANK CAR AND A SECOND 1 INCH BY 2 FOOT RIP ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR.  AREA WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER AND ELKHART FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  APPROXIMATELY TWENTY CONRAIL EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED FOR A SHORT TIME FROM A NEARBY OFFICE BUILDING. MEMBERS OF THE ELKHART FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM COVERED AND SECURED BOTH OPENINGS WITH PLASTIC.  CAR WAS ALSO INSPECTED BY AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES DISTRICT INSPECTOR D. HEALY PRIOR TO REAILING WHICH WAS COMPLETED AT 1630 HOURS, 12/28/91.  CAR WAS MOVED TO A REPAIR TRACK IN THE YARD FOR DISPOSITION. CONRAIL WILL OBTAIN AN EXEMPTION FROM THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION PRIOR TO PLACING THE CAR INTO TRANSPORTATION.

(CHROMIUM/XYLENE)" ORM-E NA 9189 (DOO7, D036, F001, F003, F004, F005) OVERTURNED IN TRANSIT AND WAS DISCOVERED BY THE DRIVER AT THE PANHANDLE TRUCK STOP ON SPRING MILLS IN MARTINSBURG, WV. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PUT DOWN A LAYER OF POLY SHEETING AND THEN A LAYER OF SPEEDI DRY.  ALL OF THE MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEASED WAS CONTAINED ON THE POLY SHEETING AND THE BACK OF THE VAN TRAILER.  THIS MATERIAL WAS COLLECTRED AND PLACED INT 8 X 55 GALLON 17H OPEN HEAD DRUMS AND WERE SENT TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA  02184.  THIS MATERIAL WILL BE SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THE DRIVERS FIRST ACTION WAS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  HE THEN CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO ENACTED THE NOTIFICATION PROCEDURES.  THE STATE OF WEST VIRGINIA WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS CHEMTREC BY CLEAN HARBORS PERSONNEL.  THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE MANAGEMENT OF THE PANHANDLE TRUCK STOP AND KEPT THEM INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THE DRIVER AND A CREW DISPATCHED FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE.  THE 2 LEAKING DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT ENSCO, INC. IN EL DORADO, ARKANSAS. IN ORDER TO PREVENT THIS SITUATION FROM HAPPENING AGAIN, DRUMS ON PALLETS WILL BE SECURED TO THE PALLET AND VERTICAL LOAD BARS WILL BE USED IN VAN TRAILS WHEN APPLICABLE.

LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERV, INC. INCURRED A HAZARDOUS WASTE SPILLAGE ON 12/31/91, BETWEEN 0930 AND 1000 HRS. THE SPILLAGE OCCURRED AT OUR TRANSPORTATION TERMINAL LOCATED AT 2202 GENOA RED BLUFF RD, HOUSTON, TX 77034. THE EPA IDENTIFICATION NUMBER ASSIGNED TO THIS LOCATION IS TXD988023305. A DRIVER WAS LOADING A ROLLOFF CONTAIENR ONTO A ROLLOFF FRAME WHEN APPROX 25 GALS OF HAZ WASTE WAS SPILLED. THE US DOT DESC OF THIS MATERIAL IS RQ, HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, N.O.S. (CONTAINS BENZENE) NA 9189, ORM-E. AN IMMEDIATE CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILLAGE WAS EXECUTED, AND AS A RESULT, APPROX 30 CUBIC YARDS OF CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS GENERATED, IN ADDITION TO ONE 85 GAL DRUM CONTAINING PLASTIC, AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT USED DURING THE CLEAN-UP. SINCE THE SPILL EXCEEDED THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY, WE CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT NO. 101290). IN ADDITION WE NOTIFIED THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION DISTRICT 7 OFFICE IN HOUSTON, TEXAS, AND THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION, EMERG RESPONSE CENTER IN AUSTIN, TX. THE TWX ASSIGNED STATE WASTE CODE 971210 TO THIS WASTE STREAM, WITH THE DESCRIPTION, "SORBENTS CONTAMINATED WITH HAZARDOUS WASTE D018R AND SOIL." THE GENERATOR WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. A SAND DIKE WAS CONSTRUCTED AROUND A 30' X 60' AREA DURING CLEANUP. SORBENT PADS AND MATERIAL WERE USED, AND CONTAMINATED SOIL AND BASE MATERIAL WERE REMOVED AND PLACED IN TWO ROLLOFF CONTAINERS. CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED AT 2000 HRS. THE EXCAVATED AREA WAS MARKOFF, AND RANDOM SAMPLES WERE TAKEN FOR ANALYSIS TO DETERMINE THAT ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL HAD BEEN REMOVED. MATERIAL GENERATED FROM THIS SPILL WILL BE ANALYZED AND DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE GOVERNMENTAL REGULATIONS. THE METHOD OF LOADING THE CONTAINER ONTO THE ROLLOFF TRAILER WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT. THE DRIVER WHO LOADED THE ROLLOFF CONTAINER HAS BEEN RE-TRAINED WITH RESPECT TO THE PROPER LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES OF ROLLOFF CONTAINERS.

column168: A PHONE CALL CAME AT 10:55 AM ON 12/18/91 FROM DETECTIVE MULLIGAN OF THE MADISON, NJ POLICE. SHE TOLD ME THAT THEY HAD STOPPED ONE OF OUR TRACTOR TRAILERS ON RT 24 IN MADISON NJ AFTER IT WAS NOTICED EMITTING A CHEMICAL FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. SHE INFORMED ME THAT OUR DRIVER AND ONE POLICE OFFICE HAD BEEN TAKEN TO MORRISTOWN MEMORIAL HOSPITAL AS WELL AS ONE CIVILIAN WHO WAS FOLLOWING OUR TRACTOR TRAILER IN A DELIVERY VAN. SHE HAD NO INFO AS TO WHAT CHEMICAL WAS LEAKING, BUT WOULD CONTACT ME IF SHE FOUND OUT ANYTHING ELSE. 4 MEMBERS WERE DISPATCHED FROM OUR HAZMAT TEAM AND 2 VEHICLES WITH A RECOVERY VESSEL, "A" SAFETY KIT, ABSORBENT AND SODIUM METABISULFATE AS THE TRAILER WAS CARRYING FULL SULFUR DIOXIDE CYLINDERS, SODIUM HYDROXIDE 19%, EMPTY ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CYLINDERS AND POTASSIUM PERMANGANATE. I ALSO CONTACTED A SALES REP OF OUR COMPANY BY MOBILE PHONE AND HAD HIM GO IMMEDIATELY TO THE LOCATION TO KEEP ME APPRISED OF THE SITUATION. I THEN CONTACTED THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES: 1) HAZARDOUS WASTE ENFORCEMENT UNIT NEW JERSEY DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION; 2) NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER; 3) MORRIS COUNTY EMERG MGMT. I THEN RECEIVED A CALL FROM CHRIS GIBBONS OF THE NJDEP FROM THE LOCATION INQUIRING IF WE HAD BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE. I EXPLAINED I HAD DISPATCHED OUR HAZMAT TEAM AND THEY WOULD BE THERE IN ABOUT AN HOUR. I WAS NOTIFIED BY OUR SALES REP AT THE SCENE THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES HAD RESPONDED:EPA,DEP, LOCAL HAZMAT, LOCAL POLICE AND LOCAL FIREFIGHTERS AND THE RELEASE APPEARED TO BE SULFUR DIOXIDE AND THE AREA HAD BEEN SECURED PENDING THE ARRIVAL OF OUR HAZMAT TEAM. UPON ARRIVAL, OUR HAZMAT TEAM DONED PROTECTIVE GEAR AND ENTERED THE TRAILER TO FIND 10 SULFUR DIOXIDE CYLINDERS AND COME LOOSE FROM THE STRAPPING AND ONE (1) CYLINDER HAD BROKEN OFF AT THE NECK, RELEASING THE ENTIRE 150 LB. CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO OUR FACILITY. AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THE STRAPPING OF THE CYLINDERS WERE NOT DONE IN ACCORDANCE WITH COMPANY POLICY AND WAS THE MAJOR CONTRIBUTING WITH ALL EMPLOYEES.

column168: ON 12/12/91, WHILE ENROUTE WITH A CYLINDER TRAILER FROM TAMAQUA, PA, TO LA PORTE, TX ON INTERSTATE 12 NEAR ALBANY, LA. OUR DRIVER NOTICED VAPORS COMING FROM THE CYLINDERS.  HE PULLED OFF THE INTERSTATE ON EXIT 39, TO INVESTIGATE THE SOURCE OF THE VAPOR.  THE DRIVER WHILE WEARING SCBA, FOUND THE LEAKER, REMOVED THE CYLINDER CAP AND TRIED TO STOP THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE HAND WHEEL, WITHOUT SUCCESS.  AFTER FAILING TO STOP THE LEAK, THE LOCAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  THE EAST AND WESTBOUND LANES OF I-12 WERE CLOSED BY AUTHORITIES AS A PRECAUTION. THE SHIPPER IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AN ER TEAM AND CONTACTED IT CORPORATION OF PORT ALLEN, LA TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE WITH THEIR CYLINDER ENCAPSULATOR.  THE CYLINDER WAS LOADED INTO THE ENCAPSULATOR AND THE VENTING TO THE ATMOSPHERE WAS STOPPED.  THE ENCAPSULATOR WAS THEN LOADED BACK ON THE TRAILER TO PROCEED TO LA PORTE, TX, ESCORTED BY THE SHIPPER EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WHICH HAD ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.

column168: A PASSING MOTORIST SPOTTED AN MG TRAILER VENTING AT THE TERMINAL.  THE MOTORIST CALLED 911 EMERGENCY AND REPORTED A PROPANE TANKER WAS ON FIRE AT THE MG FACILITY.  911 EMERGENCY DISPATCHED THE MAYO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DEHAC (DIVISION OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH AND CONTROL).  WHEN THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DEHAC ARRIVED THEY BEGAN EVACUATING THE AREA AT A 1/4 MILE RADIUS FROM THE TERMINAL.  WHILE PEOPLE WERE BEING EVACUATED AN MG DRIVER, MECHANIC AND TV CREW ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  AFTER 30 MINUTES OF STANDING AROUND TRYING TO ESTABLISH A PLAN OF ACTION, THE MG EMPLOYEES CONVINVED THE OFFICIALS TO LET THEM ON THE PROPERTY TO INSPECT THE TRAILER.  THEY DISCOVERED THE PRESSURE BUILD VALVE HAD FROZEN AND WAS NOT COMPLETELY SEALED, CAUSING THE VESSEL TO BUILD PRESSURE AND PUSH GAS AND LIQUID OUT THE DISCHARGE LINE.  THE MG EMPLOYEES THAWED OUT THE VALVE, COMPLETELY CLOSED IT AND RELEASED DOME PRESSURE FROM THE VESSEL PUTTING AN END TO THE INCIDENT.  THE EMPLOYEES REPORTED APPROX 1 GALLON OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER.  MG DRIVER TOM BRADY GRANTED THE TV CREW AN INTERVIEW AFTER THE INCIDENT, HE SAID: "THAT THE TRAILER HAD LEAKED LESS THAN A GALLON OF LIQUID OXYGEN DUE TO VALVE BEING FROZEN."

STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, STEVE RANK, THAT SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT SPLASHING FROM TOP OF CAR RUSX 3032 WHICH HAD ARRIVED ON TRAIN PKEW-09. MANAGER STINE RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT BOTH SIDES AND ENTIRE PLATFORM OF CAR WAS SATURATED WITH  PRODUCT.  MANAGER STINE FURTHER NOTED THAT SIX OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAT WRENCH TIGHT. MANAGER STINE REMOVED INTACT SEAM BAKER 2148 FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT 50% OF THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISSING. NOZZLE SURFACE WAS CLEANED AND GORTEX GASKET WAS APPLIED WHICH SECURED COVER PLATE. MANAGER STINE REMOVED INTACT SEAL BAKER 2149 FROM PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND FOUND THE PORT PLUGS IN BOTH THE LIQUID VALVE AND AIR INLET VALVE TO BE LESS THAT WRENCH TIGHT.  MANAGER STINE SAW NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE FROM EITHER VALVE. MR. T. FLORES OF CHEMTREC AND MR. STEVE NICHOLS OF BAKER/CHEMLINK WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.W. ALM WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TRAIN CREW REPORTED AMMONIA ODOR FROM TANK CAR RUSX 17022.  SSA/HM ALM RESPONDED AND MET WINNEMUCCA RURAL FIRE CHIEF, NEIL WRIGHT, AND CYANCO, JOHN SIGFREID AT THE INCIDENT.  INSPECTION DETERMINED A SLIGHT LEAK BETWEN THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE AND THE MANWAY PLATE APPARENTLY CAUSED BY A FAILED GASKET.  WATER WAS PLACED IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING TO ABSORB ANY AMMONIA FUMES AND SSA/HM ALM ACCOMPANIED TANK CAR TO DESTINATION. CHEMTREC, NEVADA DDEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY SERVICES AND MIKE KULBACKI OF THE NEVADA PUBLIC SERVICE COMISSION WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.W. ALM OBSERVED THAT TANK CAR RUSX 170023 HAD WHITE RESIDUE AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK.  SSA/HM ALM'S INSPECTION DETERMINED NO LEAKS OR PROBLEMS FROM THE TANK CAR. IT APPEARED THAT RESIDUE COULD BE SPILLAGE FROM LOADING.  FMC CORPORATION WAS NOTIFIED AND MANAGER BRUCE BLACKETTER RESPONDED.  DECISION BY WINNEMUCCA RURAL FIRE CHIEF, NEIL WRIGHT, MANAGER BLACKETTER AND SSA/HM ALM WAS MADE TO LET CAR CONTINUE TO DESTINTION, RENNOX, NV.  CAR WOULD BE CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED AT DESTINATION.  ON 12/06/91 TANK CAR WAS DELIVERED TO DESTINATION WITHOUT INCIDENT.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) G.B. REEDER WAS NOTIFIED OF A PLACARDED TRAILER LEAKING AT THE SETTEGAST PIGGYBACK RAMP.  UPON SSA/HM REEDER'S ARRIVAL, HE NOTED THAT THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN THE UPPER LOAD ON A DOUBLE STACK SHIPMENT.  PRODUCT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE LOWER CONTAINER.  ALL EXPOSED MATERIAL (PRODUCT) WAS DRY AND RUBBERY.  SSA/HM REEDER CHECKED THE WAYBILL WHICH INDICATED THE TRAILER CONTAINED DRUMS OF PAINT.  SSA/HM REEDER OPENED THE TRAILER AND INSPECTION DETERMINED NO BLOCKING OR BRACING IN THE TRAILER.  DRUMS WERE LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 10 FEET INSIDE THE DOORS AND ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS COMPLETELY EMPTY.  PRODUCT WHICH HAD SPILLED ON THE FLOOR WAS COMPLETELY DRY AND INSPECTION REVEALED NO OTHER DRUMS WERE LEAKING.  SSA/HM REEDER RELEASED TRAILER FOR MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE, DRUMS WERE PROMPTLY UNLOADED. INSPECTION DETERMINED THE BOTTOM OF ONE DRUM WAS PUSHED OUT AND THE METAL HAD BENT SHARPLY AND CRACKED ALLOWING RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE DRUM WAS RECONDITIONED AND DID NOT BEAR NAME OR DATE OF RECONDITIONING.  CHEMTREC AND UP FREIGHT CLAIMS WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS F.H. LERCH WAS NOTIFIED THAT TWO PORTABLE TANKS WERE ON THE GROUND.  SA/HM LERCH RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED #P1086 AND #P1106 HAD FALLEN OFF FLATCAR APPARENTLY FROM A LOAD SHIFT.  THE TANKS WERE PUNCTURED BY BRACING WHEN KNOCKED FROM THE FLATCAR AND A SMALL AMOUNT (1 CUP) OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  PUNCTURES WERE SEALED WITH SILICON AND TAPED OVER TO STOP RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  PORTABLE TANKS WERE RELOADED AND SECURED ONTO THE FLATCAR OF FURTHER MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC, RICHARD STEVENS, SHIPPERS DIRECTOR OF SAFETY, WARDEN WILDER, AND NEBRASKA ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL, STEVE MCNAUGHTON WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: AT APPROX 1245 HOURS MONDAY, DEC. 9, 1991, TANK CAR UELX 78044 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHILE SITTING ON NO.5 TRACK IN THE SOUTH YARD. MR. T W GRUBBS, RF&P'S SUPERVISOR POLICE AND SAFETY, WAS ADVISED OF THE LEAKING TANK CAR BY THE YARDMASTER AND MADE AN INSPECTION OF THE CAR AT 1300 HOURS. HE FOUND THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR LEAKING FROM AROUND THE COVER WHICH ENCLOSED THE UNLOADING VALVE AND FITTINGS. THE CONTENTS WERE SLOWLY RUNNING OUT AROUND THE COVER, DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND DRIPPING OFF THE BOTTOM. AT 1325 HOURS, MR. GRUBBS ATTEMPTED TO CALL MR. WILLIAM OERTLY, HAZMAT INSPECTOR OF THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES. MR. OERTLY WAS NOT IN RICHOMD. HOWEVER, MR. OERTLY WAS PAGED AND RETURNED THE CALL AT 1334 HOURS. MR. OERTLY WAS INFORMED ABOUT THE LEAK, AND HE ADVISED TO CHECK THE 2 INCH UNLOADING VALVE LOCATED UNDER THE COVER, BECAUSE SOMETIMES THE VALVE IS NOT CLOSED TIGHT AND WHEN PRESSURE BUILDS UP IN THE TANK CAR, BECAUSE OF THE RISE IN TEMPERATURE, THE CONTENTS WOULD LEAK OUT OF THE VALVE. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1350 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, ARCHER DANIELS MIDLAND COMP, OF PEORIA, IL. AT 1400 HRS MR. AASEN, HAZMAT TRANS SPEC FOR ARCHER DANIELS MIDLAND, CALLED BACK AND WAS INFORMED OF THE LEAKING TANK CAR. MR. AASEN ADVISED HE WOULD HAVE SOMEONE FROM ARCHER DANIELS MIDLAND CALL BACK TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS FOR REPAIRS. RF&P'S ASST ENGINEER, MR. J R HALL, AND MR GRUBBS WENT TO REINSPECT THE TANK CAR WHICH HAD BEEN MOVED TO THE NORTH END OF NO.1 SOUTH YARD TRACK TO ISOLATE THE CAR FROM THE YARD OPERATIONS. AFTER OPENING THE COVER WHICH CONTAINED THE UNLOADING VALVE AND FITTINGS, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE 2 INCH VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED TIGHTLY. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE LEAK STOPPED AT 1440 HRS. THE TANK CAR WAS PUT BACK INTO RAIL SERVICES AT 1450 HRS. AT 1510 HRS MR. JOHN MARTEN, SUPV OF RAIL CAR MAINTENANCE FOR ARCHER DANIELS MIDLAND, WAS CALLED AND ADVISED THE LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED AND THE TANK CAR WOULD BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE, ARCHER DANIELS MIDLAND IN FREDERICKSBURG, VA.

MR. FERRY DROPPED THE CARTONS ON THE FLOOR, CAUSING GLASS BOTTLE TO CRACK INSIDE.  TWO 4 LITER BOTTLES BROKE, CONTENTS SPILLED.  SPILL CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUM WITH BROKEN GLASS, WET CARTON AND TWO FULL BOTTLES.

LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (FS), INC. TRACTOR TRAILER LOADED WITH A ROLLOFF CONTAINER WAS PROCEEDING ON INTERSTATE 10, EASTBOUND ENROUTE TO LAIDLAW ENCIRONMENTAL SERVICES (RECOVERY), INC. FACILITY AT CROWLEY, LOUISIANA.  AT APPROXIMATELY MILE MARKER 79, THE UNIT WAS PULLED OVER BY A LOUISIANA STATE TROOPER.  THE TROOPER REPORTEDLY NOTED THAT HIS VEHICLE WAS SPRINKLED WHEN OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER PASSED HIS VEHICLE.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER A SMALL HOLE WAS FOUND ON THE FRONT SIDE OF THE ROLLOFF CONTAINER.  A RESPONSE TEAM FROM LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (RECOVERY), INC'S CROWLEY FACILITY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE, PLUGGED THE LEAK AND EFFECTED CLEANUP.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND ASSOCIATED CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN ONE 55 GALLON DRUM.  THE LOUISIANA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNIT AND THE LOUSISANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WERE NOTIFIED BY TELEPHONE.  ROY VARNADO OF THE ACADIA REGIONAL OFFICE OF THE LOUISIANA DEQ RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE DEQ ISSUED A TEMPORARY EPA ID NUMBER, LAP2300663067 AND THE DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED BY LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (RECOVERY), INC. TO THEIR CROWLEY FACILITY ON MANIFEST NO. LAA30742249.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE HAD NOT NOTED ANY LEAK AT THE TIME OF LOADING THE CONTAINER OR DURING SUBSEQUENT PERIODIC INSPECTIONS WHILE IN TRANSIT.  AFTER THE LEAK WAS STOPPED THE CONTAINER WAS ALLOWED TO PROCEED TO THE CROWLEY FACILITY.  THE CONTAINER WAS UNLOADED AND RETURNED TO THE EAST HOUSTON FACILITY FOR INSPECTION. REPAIRS WERE ACCOMPLISHED ON 12-19-91.

SA/HM LERCH'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING ROD WAS LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT (SA/HM) FRANK LERCH NOTED TANK CAR ACFX 17571 HAD A STRONG SMELL OF AMMONIA COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. SA/HM LERCH INSPECTION OF PROTECTIVE HOUSING, SEAL #CCPRR-359360, DETERMINED THE GAUGING DEVICE BODY LEAKING DUE TO UNSECURED FLANGE NUTS AND SHOULDER STUD, THE GAUGING ROD PACKING GLAND, LIQUID VALVES AND VAPOR VALVE PLUGS WERE ALSO UNSECURED. THE GAUGING ROD NEEDLE VALVE WAS LOOSE AND LEAKING FROM THE SEAT. SA/HM LERCH WRAPPED SEAT WITH TEFLON TAPE AND TIGHTENED. SA/HM LERCH APPLIED GORTEX AROUND THE BASE OF THE GAUGE HOUSING AND TIGHTENED TO SEAL FROM ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE. ALL FITTINGS WERE TIGHTENED AND LEAKS STOPPED. ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE CHECKED WITH AMMONIA LEAK DETECTOR AND NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS FOUND. SA/HM LERCH APPLIED SEAL UPC-53122 TO PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC, JOE RAZALAN, AND NEBRASKA ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL, KIRK MORROW WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THERE WAS A SLIGHT LEAK FROM THE HINGED SIDE OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND FURTHER INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE NUTS ON THE TWO HINGE SIDE SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. MGR STINE SECURED THE EYE BOLT NUTS WHICH STOPPED LEAK AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. JOE DEBMAN OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

BENETO DRIVER PETE WILLIS ARRIVED AT TEXACO BRADSHAW AT 12:00 NOON. HE HAD NO IDEA AS TO WHERE TO UNLOAD, HE CONTACTED THE SPPL OFFICE FOR INFO REGARDING TANK SIZE, CONNECTIONS, ETC. SPPL PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SCENE AND TOLD HIM THEY HAD NO INFO REGARDING THE PREVIOUS REQUESTS. HE THEN CALLED TEXACO RICHMOND, VIA CELLULAR PHONE, AND SPOKE TO BOB PACK. HE TOLD THE DRIVER WHERE THE TANK FILL CONNECTION WAS LOCATED, AND THE TANK HAD A CAPACITY OF 8,000 GALS. DALE THURMAN OF SPPL BRADSHAW WAS PRESENT DURING THE CALL, AND OVERHEARD THE CONVERSATION HE HAD WITH MR. PACK. MR. THURMAN AND THE DRIVER STUCK THE TANK TO DETERMINE PRODUCT ON HAND. THERE WAS LESS THAN ONE INCH OF PRODUCT. I THEN HOOKED UP THE TRAILER TO THE TRUCK CARGO PUMP AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD. THE DRIVER HAD 3800 GALS IN THE TRAILER AND COMPLETELY UNLOADED SAME WITH NO PROBLEMS. DRIVER THE PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD TRUCK WHICH CONTAINED 3200 GALS. HE DID NOT CHECK THE TANK BETWEEN THE OFF LOADING OF THE TRAILER AS HE HAD BEEN TOLD BY MR. PACK THAT TOTAL CAPACITY WAS 8,000 GALS, AND HE HAD ONLY 7,000 GALS TOTAL, AND THE TANK HE WAS FILLING HAD LESS THAN ONE INCH OF PRODUCT. ABOUT TEN MINUTES INTO UNLOADING OF THE TRUCK TANK, A PTC TRUCK MOMENTARILY BLOCKED THE VIEW OF THE TANK. THE DRIVER NOTICED A HEAVY ADDITIVE SMELL, AND WHEN THE PTC TRUCK CLEAR HIS VIEW OF THE TANK, ADDITIVE WAS SPRAYING OUT THE VENT AT A HIGH FLOW RATE, SPILLING ON THE GROUND. HE IMMEDIATELY CEASED PRODUCT FLOW INTO THE PUMP AND SHUT THE PUMP OFF. IT TOOK 10 SECONDS OR SO FOR THE PRODUCT TO STOP GEYSERING OUT OF THE VENT OF THE TANK. THE DRIVER DETERMINED HOW MUCH HAD SPILLED, THEN CONTACTED THE SPPL OFFICE AND REQUESTED MR. BOB MARCH OF BENETO AND TOLD HIM WHAT HAD HAPPENED. THIRDLY, HE CONTACTED MR. PACK AT TEXACO RICHMOND. HE ESTIMATES 75-100 GALLONS SPILLED. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO DISCONNECT ALL HOSES FROM THE PUMPING OPERATION AND SECURED HIS TRUCK AND AWAITED THE ARRIVAL OF BOB MARCH AND THE BENETO CLEAN-UP CREW. HE SUPPLIED A COPY OF THE MSDS (MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET) TO TEXACO'S CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR. DISPATCH HAD HIM TAKE THE REMAINING PRODUCT, (DETERMINED BY STICKING THE TRUCK TANK AND CHECKING TRUCK TANK CALIBRATION CHARTS) 1605 GALS, TO TEXACO RICHMOND. HE CHECKED WITH BOB MARCH TO SEE IF HE WAS NEEDED FOR FURTHER INFO, AND WAS RELEASED FROM THE SPILL SITE AT ABOUT 2:30PM.

column168: MIKE MCBAY, CITY P&D DRIVER/SALEMAN, WAS UNLOADING THE (33) DRUMS AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION. THE AREA WHERE THE DRUMS WERE UNLOADED WAS A CONCRETE YARD, FENCED, WITH NO DOCK AVAILABLE. AS MCBAY WAS UNLOADING ONE OF THE DRUMS, IT SLIPPED OFF THE BARREL WHEELER, DROPPED TO THE GROUND, AND SEPARATED AROUND THE RIM. THE AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY PERSONNEL WITH NUTONE. THE DRIVER WAS ISSUED A LETTER OF INSTRUCTION, AND ADVISED TO BE MORE CAREFUL IN THE FUTURE WHEN WORKING WITH 55 GAL DRUMS.

column62: Abrasion; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: ON DECEMBER 10, 1991 NORFOLK SOUTHERN TRAIN CREW SHOVED A CUT OF CARS ONTO BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN RAILROAD PROPERTY AT 34TH ST YARD.  UPON INSPECTION OF CARS BY CAR INSPECTOR LARRY RICE, TANK CAR GATX 39774 WAS FOUND WITH A DRIP COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF CAR. MR. JAMES KIRBY OF ALLIED CHEMICAL WAS SENT TO CORRECT THE LEAK.  HE ADVISED THAT THE CAP ON THE BOTTOM VALVE WAS LOOSE.  HE TIGHTENED THE CAP AND SEALED AROUND THE EDGE OF THE CAP.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON 12/13/91, AT APPROXIMATELY 0207, KYLE MURPHEY (RAMP SUPERVISOR) REPORTED A PINK LIQUID ON THE GROUND NEAR ONE OF OUR AIRCRAFTS.  I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, RESPONDED TO THE CALL.  I FOUND 1 X 1 GALLON OF PAINT LEAKING.  THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS LEAKING WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBREBOARD BOX THAT WAS MARKED "CONSUMER COMMODITY ORM-D".  THERE WERE NO OTHER HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUT PACKAGING.  INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS 1 X 1 GALLON PAINT CAN (CONTENTS COMPLETELY LOST).  THE PAINT CAN WAS METAL, WITH A FRICTION TYPE LID.  THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE LID TO THE METAL CAN.  THERE WAS NO SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION FOR THIS SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT HAS BEEN REPACKED IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND TRUCKED BACK TO THE ORIGIN.

IN ORDER TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURANCES, WE MUST INSURE THAT ALL TOTE TANKS ARE PROPERLY CAPPED AND SEALED AT TIME OF PICK UP. ON WEDNESDAY DEC 18TH 1991 ABOUT 2:30PM I WAS DELIVERING TWO TOTE TANKS TO ALCO CHEMICAL CO. WHEN THE FORK LIFT DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD THE SECOND, TOTE TANK HE NOTICED LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF TRAILER.  AT THIS POINT HE CALLED THE LEADMAN, MARK OVER TO CHECK THE TANK.  UPON INSPECTION OF TANK HE FOUND THE CAP COMPLETELY OFF TANK, THUS CAUSING LIQUID TO SPLASH OUT FROM THE MOVEMENT OF TRAILER OVER THE ROAD.  THE LIQUID HAD RUN WITHIN TWO FEET OF FRONT OF TRAILER, THUS CAUSING SOME OF THE BOXES TO GET DAMP.  MARK COMMENTED THE LOCK TABS ON CONTAINER WAS NOT PROPERLY SEALED, & TAPED FOR SHIPMENT.  AT THIS TIME MONITER WHO IS IN CHARGE OF SHIPPING & RECIEVING CAME OUT ON THE DOCK.  MARK THEN EXPLAINED TO HER AS WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS. THEY TOLD ME TO MOVE MY TRUCK AWAY FROM DOCK AND ONTO THE YARD.  THEY HAD ALREADY CONTACTED THE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION PERSONNEL, ALREADY ON THE SITE.  ABOUT 45 MINUTES LATER I WAS TOLD TO PUT MY TRUCK TO THE DOCK AT THIS TIME THE EPA PERSONNEL WENT ONTO TRAILER TO ACCESS THE PROBLEM.  THEY TOLD ONE OF THE SECOND SHIFT EMPLOYEES (CHARLES) WHAT TO DO ABOUT THE SPILLAGE IN TRAILER, AND ALSO THE REMAINING SHIPMENTS ON THE TRAILER. THE PULLED EVERYTHING OFF THE TRAILER AND PLACED ON THEIR DOCK. I THEN MOVED THE TRAILER TO A LOCATION TO BE CLEANED OUT.  AFTER TRAILER WAS CLEANED WE REBOXED THE SHIPMENT WHERE THE BOXES WERE DAMP.  HE THEN LOADED EVERYTHING BACK ON THE TRAILER.  AT THIS TIME I PROCEEDED TO TERMINAL.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: 1405 HOURS:  I WAS NOTIFIED BY KATHY HOLCOMB, OP&C, THAT IN TRACK 107 OF THE RECEIVING YARD AT COLTON. CALIFORNIA. TLDX 114016, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  SHE ADVISED ME AT THIS TIME THAT KEITH KEELIN, TRAINMASTER COLTON, HAD INSPECTED THE CAR AND WAS UNABLE TO COMPLETELY STOP THE LEAK.  SHE ALSO ADVISED ME THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN ADVISED AND WAS IN RESPONSE.  I ADVISED MS. HOLCOMB THAT I WOULD MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  1415 HOURS:  CONTACTD D.J. JOHNSON, SP HAZ.MAT OFFICER IN SAN ANTONIO, TX AND ADVISED THAT I WAS IN RESPONSE TO THE SCENE.  1420 HOURS:  CONTACTED DIABLO JET CENTER AT CONCORD AND MADE FLIGHT ARRANGEMENTS.  1430 HOURS:  CONTACTED KIETH KEELIN AT COLTON WHILE ENROUTE AND ASKED HIM TO BRIEF ME ON THE SITUATION.  HE ADVISED ME THAT WHEN HE FIRST INSPECTED THE CAR, THE CAR WAS LEAKING AT A RATE 305 DROPS PER SECOND, AND WAS ABLE TO REDUCE THE LEAK TO 1-3 DROPS PER SECOND BY ADJUSTING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE.  HE WAS UNABLE TO COMPLETELY STOP THE LEAK WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO SECURE ALL NUTS AND BOLTS ON THE VALVE ASSEMBLY. THE LEAK WAS BEING CONTAINED WITH A 35 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER.  HE ALSO STATED THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE.  I THEN SPOKE WITH CAPTAIN MCCLINTOCK AND ADVISED HIM THAT I WAS IN RESPONSE FROM OAKLAND WITH NECESSARY PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND TOOLS TO REPAIR THE CAR.  I ADVISED HIM THAT MY ETA WAS 1800 HOURS AND THAT ARRANGEMENTS WERE BEING MADE TO ISOLATE THE CAR FROM ENTRY WITH OUR SP POLICE DEPARTMENT. HE WAS SATISFIED WITH OUR ACTIONS AND ADVISED ME THAT HE WAS DEPARTING THE SCENE.  1815 HOURS:  ARRIVED SCENE AND MADE INSPECTION WITH CAR FOREMAN TONY VASGUEZ.  WE DISCOVERED THE WAFER VALVE STUDS, WHICH SECURES THE VALVE TO THE TANK CAR, WERE TOO LONG, WHICH PREVENTED THE 4" FLANGE ASSEMBLY FROM MAKING A FLUSH FIT ON THE GASKET WHERE IT ATTACHED TO THE 6" WAFER VALVE.  (NOTE HI-LITED AREA ON PHOTOS).  TO CORRECT, THE STUDS WERE TRIMMED WITH A HACK SAW, TO ALLOW FOR A FLUSH FIT WITH THE GASKET ON THE WAFER VALVE.  WHILE PERFORMING THE REPAIRS, THE LOWER PORTION OT THE VALVE ASSEMBLY HAD TO BE REMOVED.  THE LEAK FROM THE VALVE NEVER STOPPED WHICH INDICATES THAT THE SHIPPER FAILED TO COMPLY WITH CFR 49, SECTION 173.31 (B)(1) AND 173.31 (B)(3).  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD CONTAMINATED THE GROUND DIRECTLY UNDER THE TANK CAR.  THIS WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH SOLUTION UNTIL A PH OF 6-7 WAS ACHIEVED. PRODUCT AND CONTAMINATED CLOTHING THAT WAS GENERATED IN THE 35 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER, WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH SP UTILITY DEPARTMENT, TOM BEESE, AT COLTON.  0010 HOURS:  12/22/91.  JOB COMPLETED AND DEPARTED SCENE.  OP&C, WRTC, AND D.J. JOHNSON ADVISED.

ON DEC, 30 1991 OUR DRIVER, JOHN SHEETS, WAS TO UNLOAD #2 FUEL OIL INTO TANK DESIGNATED BY MANAGER OF DRIVERS HEATING.  THE VALVE WAS TO BE OPENED BY MANAGER FOR THE CORRECT TANK.  FAILED TO OPEN VALVE FILLING SMALLER TANK AND OVERFLOWING. PRODUCT.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE DIKE AREA AROUND TANK.  MANAGER ASSUMED FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR SPILLAGE.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO AGWAY IN LIBERTY N.Y. WITH A LOAD OF #2 HEATING OIL FOR TANK #3.  TANK#3 WOULD NOT ACCEPT THE WHOLE LOAD SO THE DRIVER WAS ADVISED BY AQWAY TERMINAL MANAGER TO SEE IF TANK #9 WOULD ACCEPT THE REMAINDER OF HIS LOAD.  OUR DRIVER READ THE GUAGE ON TANK #9 THEN WENT TO HIS TANK CHART CALIBRATION BOOK TO DETERMINE THE GALLONS. OUR DRIVER THOUGHT THE TANK DIAMETER WAS 126" WHEN IN FACT IT WAS ONLY 120". THIS CAUSED AOUR DRIVER TO OVERESTIMATE THE AVAILABLE ROOM IN TANK #9. OUR DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO START PUMPING INTO TANK 9 CAUSING  THE TANK TO OVER FILL AND FUEL TO COME OUT THE VENT LINE ON TOP.  SPILL WAS CONFINED TO CONTAINMENT AREA UNDER TANK.  NEW YORK STATE DEPT.  OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #9110184 TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: MANAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY MYO STEVE TROUTMAN THAT SWITCH CREWS NOTED A SLIGHT DRIP OF PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON CAR GATX 21199. DUE TO THE FACT MANAGER STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, CHIEF INSPECTOR OF THE ARR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, MR. A.D. MATY, WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO RESPONSE. INSPECTOR MATY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS APPARENTLY NOT SEATED.  ADDITIONAL PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO THE VALVE ROD AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  INSPECTOR MATY ALSO FOUND THAT THE GASKET ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS IN NEED OF REPLACEMENT.  INSPECTOR MATY REPLACED GASKET AND CAR SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF FURTHER LEAKAGE. INSPECTOR MATY NOTIFIED CHEMTREC OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE, WAS NOTIFIED BY MYO JACK FURLONG THAT CAR TGAX 121011 WAS SPLASHING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCHING. DUE TO THE FACT MANAGER STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, CHIEF INSPECTOR FOR AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, MR. A.D. MATY WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND. CHIEF INSPECTOR MATY RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE "FDI", 100 PSI. FRANGIBLE DISC HAD FAILED.  THE FAILED DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW DISC AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTAION. INSPECTOR MATY NOTIFIED JOE DEBMAN AT CHEMTREC OF THE INCIDENT.

FLORIDA WEST AIRLINES FLIGHT 301 DEPARTED KMIA AT 1845, DESTINED FOR MANAGUA, NICARAGUA.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS A B707-320, REGISTRATION N527SJ AND THE CREW CONSISTED OF CAPTAIN DAVID JENKS, F/O PETER SMITH AND F/E EDUARDO CERRA.  THE FLIGHT HAD BEEN CHARTERED TO FLORIDA WEST AGENCY, A SAN JOSE, COSTA RICA BASED FREIGHT FORWARDING COMPANY. APPROXIMATELY 5 MINUTES AFTER DEPARTURE, THE CREW BECAME AWARE OF A CHLORINE ODOR IN THE COCKPIT.  IN RESPONSE, THEY TURNED BACK TO MIAMI AND ADVISED MIAMI TOWER AND FLORIDA WEST FLIGHT CONTROL OF THEIR PROBLEM. FLIGHT CONTROL, IN TURN, ADVISED THE F.A.A. HAZMAT F.S.D.D., MR JOSEPH OCHOA.  THE PLANE LANDED WITHOUT INCIDENT AT 1855 AND TAXIED TO THE FLORIDA WEST RAMPED WHERE THE CREW DEPLANED. INVESTIGATION BY FLORIDA WEST DETERMINED THE SMELL WAS CONCENTRATED IN THE COCKPIT AND THE LOWER 41, WITH NO ODOR IN THE MAIN CABIN.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY THE MX STAFF LOCATED TWO CYLINDERS WHICH WERE STAMPED CHLORINE.  THE BOTTLES HAD BEEN MANIFESTED AS EMPTY CYLINDERS DESTINED FOR MANAGUA, NICARAGUA.  THE CAPTAIN HAD THE BOTTLES REMOVED AND AFTER AIRING OUT THE AIRCRAFT DEPARTED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: SSA/HM TM ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR DOWX 4244 WAS INVOLVED IN A LOW SPEED DERAILMENT AT UPRR YARD AT AMA, LOUISIANA. INITIAL REPORT INDICATED THAT THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE FROM TANK CAR. SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED AND DERAILMENT CAUSED CAR TO LIST 45 DEGREES CAUSING DAMAGE TO RUNNING GEAR AND EXTERNAL SAFETY APPLIANCES. FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED A SLOW DRIP OF PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE OPERATING ROD PACKING GLAND ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. SSA/HM ROBINSON TIGHTENED THE TWO RETAINING NUTS ON THE PACKING GLAND RETAINER AND LEAK STOPPED. CAR WAS TRANSFERRED TO GATX 57099 AND ONCE EMPTIED DOWX 4244 WAS RERAILED. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC, DOW CHEM, THE LA STATE POLICE, THE LA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, THE ST CHARLES PARISH SHERRIF'S OFFOCE AND THE LUING, LA VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: OUR DRIVER, ANGEL VAZQUEZ, STOPPED AT THE REST AREA ON I-10 EAST, MILEPOST 182. HE WAS MAKING HIS VEHICLE CHECK AND NOTED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TRAILER. OUR DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL THEN OPENED THE TRAILER TO IDENTIFY THE LEAKING CONTAINER. OUR DRIVER CONTACTED THE DEPT OF SAFETY IN ARIZONA THEN CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE US COAST GUARD NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO REPORT THE SPILL. THE ARIZONA HIGHWAY PATROL CONTACTED RESNA/EXCELTECH, INC. TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL, REPACKAGE ANY LEAKING CONTAINERS, AND CLEAN THE TRAILER. DURING CLEANUP THE LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE FOUND TO BE ONE 5 GAL CANS OF 2,4-DICHLOROPHENOZYACETIC ASPHALT CONTAMINATED BY THE SPILL WAS REMOVED AND THE AREA WAS REPAVED. THE ASPHALT AND PLASTIC RESULTING FROM CLEANUP WERE DRUMMED AND TAKEN TO RINCHEM COMPANY, 1550 W LOWER BUCKEYE RD, PHOENIX, AZ FOR STORAGE UNTIL DISPOSAL IS ARRANGED. THE REPACKAGED HERBICIDE AND PAINT WERE TAKEN ON TO FINAL DISPOSAL. THE REST STOP ATTENDANT, HIS WIFE , AND OUR DRIVER WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR EXAMINATION AND RELEASED IMMEDIATELY.

column168: RICHARD HAASE SET THE CARTON ON THE GROUND AND IT STARTED LEAKING.  HE SAID THE BOTTLE INSIDE MUST HAVE ALREADY BEEN BROKEN.  FULLER'S EARTH WAS USED TO CLEAN THE SPILL.  PRODUCT EVAPORATED, NO RESIDUE REMAINED.

column168: CSX TRANSPORTATION RECEIVED CALL OF A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE RAMP IN SAVANNAH, GA.  THE RAMP NOTIFIED THE LOCAL STEAMSHIP CO, JOHN JAMES, WHO WAS TO RECEIVE THE LOAD.  JOHN JAMES NOTIFIED CHEMTREC.  CSXT HAZMAT FOLLOWED UP WITH CHEMTREC WHEN SHIPPER DID NOT RESPOND, HAZMAT CALLED A JACKSONVILLE, FL BASED CLEANUP CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND.  CONTRACTOR FOUND 1 55 GAL DRUM AT BACK OF CONTAINER WITH A CRUSHED CHIME, DUE TO DOOR CLOSING ON IT AND 1 OTHER SUSPECTED OF LEAKING BUT NO SIGN OF CAUSE.  BOTH DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column168: ON DECEMBER 30, 1991 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:55 PM, CSX TRAIN CREW SHOVED 34TH ST. YARD WITH A CUT OF CARS.  BSRR CAR INSPECTOR DWIGHT GENTRY UPON HIS INSPECTION OF TRAIN FOUND TLDX 23001 WITH AN UNLATCHED DOME COVER.  A MILKY LOOKING SUBSTANCE HAD LEAKED FROM DOME DOWN THE SIDE OF TANK CAR. SUBSTANCE DID NOT REACH GROUND. MR. TIM O'TOOLE OF KOPPERS TAR PLANT WAS CALLED.  MR. O'TOOLE FOUND A KINKED GASKET ON DOME LID.  GASKET WAS REPAIRED AND DOME WAS CLOSED.  THEY WIPED SUBSTANCE OFF OF CAR AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR SERVICE.  PLEASE FIND ATTACHED A COPY OF REPORT FROM ASST. TRAINMASTER RAY FANCHER.

0830 HOURS: WAS NOTIFIED BY WARREN MATHEY, PC&C, THAT UTLX 48115 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE TANK CAR WHEN MOVING.  HE ADVISED ME THAT THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE POCKET TRACK AT WARM SPRINGS YARD AND THE CONTENTS BUTYL ACETATE. 0845 HOURS: NOTIFIED H.L. BART AND D.W. SNOW OF THE SITUATION.  ALSO CONTACTED SP POLICE AND REQUESTED ASSISTANCE AT THE SCENE. 0945 HOURS: ARRIVED SCENE AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  FOUND THE VACUUM BREAKER VALVE SHAFT BROKEN.  MADE TEMPORARY REPAIRS BY REMOVING THE BROKEN PARTS AND APPLIED A REDWOOD PLUG WITH A NEOPRENE GASKET. 1110 HOURS: CONTACTED JIM ZEAGAS OF ASHLAND CHEMICAL WHERE THE CAR WAS CONSIGNED AT (415) 796-933 AND ADVISED HIM OF THE TEMPORARY REPAIR AND REQUESTED TO HAVE THE CAR REPAIRED PROPERLY AFTER UNLOADING. 1130 HOURS: CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, JIM BAILEY OF UNION CARBIDE AT (304) 747-7572 AND INFORMED HIM OF MY FINDINGS AND OF THE TEMPORARY REPAIRS MADE.  I ALSO REQUESTED THAT THE CAR BE REPAIRED PROPERLY AFTER UNLOADING. 1200 HOURS: CONTACTED H.L. BART AND D.W. SNOW AND ADVISED OF SITUATION AND DEPARTED SCENE. DUE TO THE DEFECTIVE VACUUM BREAKER VALVE, APPROXIMATELY 1 QT. OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED WHICH WAS CONFINED TO THE DOME AREA OF THE TANK CAR.

ON 12-10-91 A SORTER APPROACH CERT 13 AT 0155 AND WAS TOLD THAT AN EXPRESS LETTER WAS LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID.  THIS PACKAGE ALSO HAD AN ODOR, LOCATED ON LATERAL 30. AT 0158 THIS INFORMATION WAS GIVEN TO ILN HAZMAT DISPATCH CIA RADIO.  0158 CERT 13, (JEFFREY A. HOSTETLER) HAZMAT COORDINATOR, WAS ON THE SCENE. THIS SPILL WAS LOCATED IN THE EXPRESS LATERALS, IN BUILDING C OF AIRBORNE EXPRESS INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. THE SPILL WAS COMING FROM ONE WHITE EXPRESS LETTER.  THE LIQUID HAS A PH OF 1 (ACID).  THE LETTER WAS IMMEDIATELY BAGGED AND THE AREA CLEANED OF ALL RESIDUE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD ASIDE IN THE HAZMAT LOCKER FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AT A LATER TIME, CLEAR OF THE SCENE AT 0200. LATER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS 2 - 4 OZ. WHITE PLASTIC CONTAINERS AND 1 SMALL GLASS TUBE WITH RED STOPPERS IN EACH END.  THE FIRST PLASTIC CONTAINER WAS EMPTY; ALL CONTENTS HAD LEAKED OUT.  THE SCREW TOP CLOSURE HAD NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  THIS CONTAINER WAS LABELED "AC 1910049 #2".  THE SECOND PLASTIC CONTAINER CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 1 OZ OF FLUID.  THE SCREW TOP CLOSURE HAD NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE AND WAS LABELED "AC 190048 #1" BOTH OF THESE LIQUIDS WERE ACID.  THE THIRD ITEM WAS A GLASS TUBE CONTAINING A BLACK GRANULAR MATERIAL.  THIS TUNE WAS LABELED "AC 1910047".  THIS TUBE WAS WRAPPED IN A PAPER TOWEL WITH CLEAR TAPE SECURING THE TOWEL. THE OUTER CONTAINER WAS A WHITE, LIGHT WEIGHT FIBERBOARD AIRBORNE EXPRESS LETTER ENEVELOPE.  THE FRONT CONTAINED THE AIRWAY BILL AND STATED THE FOLLOWING: AWB: HPN 684532855 WRN 5-C  FROM: GENERAL MOROS, 199 BEEKMAN AVENUE, NORTH TARRYTOWN, NY 10591 MICHAEL MARTIN 1-914-337-4622. TO: GM I.H. DEPT 3-229 RESEARCH ADM BLD., GM TECH BLDG 30500 MOUND ROAD, WARREN, MI.  DOC DON HART 48090-9055. THIS SHIPMENT WAS BROUGHT TO THE HAS SORT ILN AND WAS HELD IN THE SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  NO MSDS WAS OBTAINED AND WAS THEN HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT RETURNED TO ORIGIN BY SHIPPERS REQUEST, AFTER THE FAA INVESTIGATION.

TRAIN 332-30 HAD GENERAL DERAILMENT OF 15 CARS AT BATES CITY, MO AT 1355 ON 12/30/91, DUE TO BROKEN RAIL.  OFFICERS AT SCENE OR FIRE CHIEF DID NOT OBSERVE ANY HAZMAT SPILL.  REPORTS TO THIS OFFICE DID NOT REVEAL ANY HAZMAT RELEASE.  ON 3/4/92, FRA INSPECTOR PATRICK A. PATTON REPORTED TO ME BY TELEPHONE THAT AT ABOUT 1930 ON 12/30. HE OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WHICH HAD LEAKED FROM INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AROUND VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, ON UTLX 78233, AND WAS SOLIDIFIED ON THE CAR.  MR. PATTON ADVISED THAT HE INFORMED OUR TM/RFE W.A. HARRIS OF HIS FINDINGS THE NEXT MORNING; HOWEVER, MR. HARRIS ADVISED HE DOES NOT RECALL THAT CONVERSATION. ON RECEIPT OF MR. PATTON'S REPORT TO THIS OFFICE, WE ARE NOW MAKING THIS REPORT.
